on Rae Signs With WME (Exclusive) |last=Jarvey |first=Natalie |date=January 21, 2020 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{TikTok}}\n* {{Instagram}}\n* {{IMDb name}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rae, Addison}}\n[[Category:2000 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American dancers]]\n[[Category:American female dancers]]\n[[Category:American TikTokers]]\n[[Category:Female TikTokers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Lafayette, Louisiana]]\n", "name_user": "82.18.186.221", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(I think I did it well!)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Addison_Rae"}
{"title_page": "Furlong", "text_new": "{{Other uses}}\n{{short description|Unit of length equal to 660 feet or about 201 meters}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2012}}\n{{Infobox unit\n| standard = [[imperial units|imperial]]/[[US customary units|US]]&nbsp;units\n| quantity = [[length]]\n| units1   = imperial/US&nbsp;units\n| inunits1 = 220&nbsp;[[yard (unit)|yd]]\n| units2   = [[metric system|metric]] ([[SI]]) units\n| inunits2 = {{convert|220|yd|m|4|lk=on|disp=out}}\n}}\n{{Anthropic_Farm Units}}\n\nA '''furlong''' is a measure of [[distance]] in [[imperial units]] and [[U.S. customary units]] equal to one eighth of a [[mile]], equivalent to 660 [[foot (unit)|feet]], 220 [[yard]]s, 40 [[rod (unit)|rods]],  10 [[chain (unit)|chains]] or approximately 201 [[meter]]s.\n\nTo measure one just ask Kevin\n\nIn the [[United States]] some states use older definitions for surveying purposes, leading to variations in the length of the furlong of two parts per million, or about 0.4 millimetre ({{frac|64}} inch). This variation is too small to have practical consequences in most applications. \n \nUsing the international definition of the [[inch]] as exactly 25.4 [[millimetre]]s, one furlong is 201.168 metres. Five furlongs are about 1 [[kilometre]] ({{convert|5/8|mi|5|disp=out}} is the exact value, according to the international conversion).\n\n==History==\nThe name ''furlong'' derives from the [[Old English language|Old English]] words ''{{lang|ang|furh}}'' (furrow) and ''{{lang|ang|lang}}'' (long).<ref>{{Cite EB1911 |wstitle=Furlong |volume=11 |page=358}}</ref> Dating back at least to early [[Anglo-Saxon]] times, it originally referred to the length of the furrow in one [[acre]] of a ploughed [[open-field system|open field]] (a medieval communal field which was divided into strips). The furlong (meaning furrow length) was the distance a team of oxen could plough without resting. This was standardised to be exactly 40 rods or 10 chains. The system of long furrows arose because turning a team of oxen pulling a heavy plough was difficult. This offset the drainage advantages of short furrows and meant furrows were made as long as possible. An acre is an area that is one furlong long and one [[Chain (unit)|chain]] (66 feet or 22 yards) wide. For this reason, the furlong was once also called an '''acre's length''',<ref>{{cite book |title=[[The Winter's Tale]] |first=William |last=Shakespeare |authorlink=William Shakespeare |edition=unabridged|publisher=Courier Dover|year=2000 |isbn=9780486411187| page=5|quotation=footnote 17: ''heat an acre''; run a heat or course of an acre's length, \"acre\" being used as a lineal measure, equivalent to a furlong.}} {{Shakecite|WT|M|1|2}}</ref> though in modern usage an area of one acre can be of any shape. The term furlong, or '''shot''', was also used to describe a grouping of adjacent strips within an open field.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=1tgk_UNST2kC&lpg=PR28&dq=furlong%20shot%20strip%20field&pg=PR28#v=onepage |title=The English Village Community Examined in Its Relation to the Manorial and Tribal Systems and to the Common Or Open Field System of Husbandry: An Essay in Economic History|first=Frederic |last=Seebohm |publisher=Cambridge University Press |date=8 Dec 2011|page=4|isbn=9781108036344}}</ref>\n\nAmong the early Anglo-Saxons, the rod was the fundamental unit of land measurement. A furlong was 40 rods; an acre 4 by 40 rods, or 4 rods by 1 furlong, and thus 160 square rods. At the time, the Saxons used the North German foot, which was 10 percent longer than the foot of today. When England changed to the shorter foot in the late 13th century, rods and furlongs remained unchanged, since property boundaries were already defined in rods and furlongs. The only thing that changed was the number of feet and yards in a rod or a furlong, and the number of square feet and square yards in an acre. The definition of the rod went from 15 old feet to {{frac|16|1|2}} new feet, or from 5 old yards to {{frac|5|1|2}} new yards. The furlong went from 600 old feet to 660 new feet, or from 200 old yards to 220 new yards. The acre went from 36,000 old square feet to 43,560 new square feet, or from 4,000 old square yards to 4,840 new square yards.<ref>{{cite book|last=Zupko|first=Ronald Edward|authorlink=Ronald Edward Zupko|title=British weights & measures: a history from antiquity to the seventeenth century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pWUgAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=26 November 2011|year=1977|publisher=University of Wisconsin Press|isbn=978-0-299-07340-4|pages=10\u201311, 20\u201321}}</ref>\n\nThe furlong was historically viewed as being equivalent to the [[Ancient Roman units of measurement|Roman stade (''stadium'')]],<ref>Compare [[Josephus]], ''[[Antiquities of the Jews|Antiquities]]'' (15.11.3), who writes of the [[Temple Mount]] in Jerusalem that it was encompassed by a wall which measured one ''stadion'' ([[Greek language|Gr.]] \u03c3\u03c4\u03ac\u03b4\u03b9\u03bf\u03bd) to each angle, a word translated in English as \"furlong.\"</ref> which in turn derived from the [[Ancient Greek units of measurement|Greek system]]. For example, the [[King James Version|King James Bible]] uses the term \"furlong\" in place of the Greek ''stadion'', although more recent translations often use miles or kilometres in the main text and give the original numbers in footnotes.\n\nIn the Roman system, there were 625 feet to the ''stadium'', eight ''stadia'' to the mile, and three miles to the [[league (unit)|league]]. A league was considered to be the distance a man could walk in one hour, and the mile (from ''mille'', \"meaning thousand\") consisted of 1,000 ''passus'' (paces, five feet, or double-step).\n\nAfter the fall of the [[Western Roman Empire]], medieval Europe continued with the Roman system, which the people proceeded to diversify, leading to serious complications in trade, taxation, etc. Around the year 1300, by royal decree England standardized a long list of measures. Among the important units of distance and length at the time were the [[foot (unit)|foot]], [[yard]], [[rod (unit)|rod]] (or pole), furlong, and the [[mile]]. The rod was defined as {{frac|5|1|2}} yards or {{frac|16|1|2}} feet, and the mile was eight furlongs, so the definition of the furlong became 40 rods and that of the mile became 5,280 feet (eight furlongs/mile times 40 rods/furlong times {{frac|16|1|2}} feet/rod).\n\nA description from 1675 states, \"Dimensurator or Measuring Instrument whereof the mosts usual has been the Chain, and the common length for English Measures four Poles, as answering indifferently to the Englishs Mile and Acre, 10 such Chains in length making a Furlong, and 10 single square Chains an Acre, so that a square Mile contains 640 square Acres.\" \u2014John Ogilby, Britannia, 1675\n\nThe official use of the furlong was abolished in the United Kingdom under the [[Weights and Measures Acts of the United Kingdom|Weights and Measures Act]] 1985, an act that also abolished the official use of many other traditional units of measurement.\n\n==Use==\n[[File:Naypyitaw Tollbooth.jpg|right|thumb|Present-day use of furlongs on a highway sign near [[Yangon]]]]\n[[File:Milepost 358-6 on Yangon-Mandalay Expressway.JPG|right|thumb|Mileposts on the Yangon\u2013Mandalay Expressway use miles followed by furlongs]]\nIn [[Myanmar]], furlongs are currently used in conjunction with miles to indicate distances on highway signs. Mileposts on the [[Yangon\u2013Mandalay Expressway]] use miles and furlongs.\n\n[[File:036175 5 furlong.jpg|right|thumb|The five-furlong (1000 m) post on [[Epsom Derby|Epsom Downs]]]]\nIn the rest of the world, the furlong has very limited use, with the notable exception of [[horse racing]] in most English-speaking countries, including [[Canada]] and the [[United States]]. The distances for [[Horse racing#Australia|horse racing]] in Australia were converted to metric in 1972,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://museumvictoria.com.au/about/mv-news/2010/how-to-measure-a-racehorse/ |title=How to measure a racehorse |year=2010 |publisher=Museum Victoria |accessdate=21 June 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150621172623/http://museumvictoria.com.au/about/mv-news/2010/how-to-measure-a-racehorse/ |archive-date=21 June 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> but in the [[United Kingdom]],<ref>[http://www.sportinglife.com/racing/goodwood/course/ Example of the use of furlongs in horse racing] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629220021/http://www.sportinglife.com/racing/goodwood/course/ |date=29 June 2011 }}</ref> [[Ireland]], [[Canada]], and the [[United States]], races are still given in miles and furlongs. Also distances along the canals in English navigated by [[narrowboat]]s are commonly expressed in miles and furlongs.\n\nThe city of [[Roads and expressways in Chicago|Chicago's street numbering system]] allots a measure of 800 address units to each mile, in keeping with the city's system of eight blocks per mile. This means that every block in a typical Chicago neighborhood (in either North/South or East/West direction but rarely both) is approximately one furlong in length. [[Salt Lake City]]'s blocks are also each a square furlong in the downtown area. The blocks become less regular in shape farther from the center, but the numbering system (800 units to each mile) remains the same everywhere in [[Salt Lake County, Utah|Salt Lake County]]. Blocks in central [[Logan, Utah]], and in large sections of [[Phoenix, Arizona]], are similarly a square furlong in extent (eight to a mile, which explains the series of freeway exits: 19th Ave, 27th, 35th, 43rd, 51st, 59th \u2026). City blocks in the [[Hoddle Grid]] of [[Melbourne]] are also one furlong in length.\n\nMuch of [[Ontario]], Canada, was originally surveyed on a ten-furlong grid, with major roads being laid out along the grid lines. Now that distances are shown on road signs in kilometres, these major roads are almost exactly two kilometres apart. The exits on highways running through [[Toronto]], for example, are generally at intervals of two kilometres.<ref>[https://www.empm.ca/reports/Title%20Searches.pdf The Importance of Title Searches] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070709160457/http://www.empm.ca/reports/Title%20Searches.pdf |date=9 July 2007 }}</ref><ref>[http://wall-arm.ca/2011/04/land-titles-vs-land-registry Land Titles vs. Land Registry]</ref>\n\nThe furlong is also a base unit of the humorous [[FFF system]] of units.<ref name=\"SKB\">Stan Kelly-Bootle, \"[http://portal.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=1229919 As Big as a Barn?]\", ''ACM Queue'', March 2007, pp. 62\u201364.</ref>\n\n==Definition of length==\n<!-- This section is linked from the lead section -->\nThe exact length of the furlong varies slightly among English-speaking countries. In Canada<ref>\n[http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/W-6/ Weights and Measures Act, R.S.C., 1985], as amended; Schedule&nbsp;II, Canadian Units of Measurement.\n</ref> and the United Kingdom,<ref>\n[http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1985/72 Weights and Measures Act 1985], as amended; Schedule&nbsp;1,\nPart&nbsp;VI, Definitions of certain units which may not be used for trade except as supplementary indications.\n</ref> which define the furlong in terms of the international yard of exactly 0.9144 metres, a furlong is 201.168&nbsp;m.\nAustralia<ref>\n[http://www.comlaw.gov.au/Series/F1999B00110 National Measurement Regulations 1999], Statutory Rules 1999 No. 110 as amended, Schedule&nbsp;11, Conversion Factors.\n</ref> does not formally define the furlong, but it does define the chain and link in terms of the international yard.\n\nIn the United States, which defines the furlong, chain, rod, and [[link (unit)|link]] in terms of the [[U.S. survey foot]] of exactly {{fract|1200|3937}} metre,<ref>\nNIST Special Publication 811, Guide for the Use of the International System of Units (SI), [http://physics.nist.gov/Pubs/SP811/appenB.html Appendix&nbsp;B], B.6, U.S. survey foot and mile. National Institute for Standards and Technology, U.S. Department of Commerce, 2008.</ref> a furlong is approximately 201.1684 m long. The United States does not formally define a \"survey yard\". The difference of approximately two parts per million between the U.S. value and the \"international\" value is insignificant for most practical measurements.  \n\nIn October 2019, [[U.S. National Geodetic Survey]] and [[National Institute of Standards and Technology]] announced their joint intent to retire the U.S. survey foot, with effect from the end of 2022. The furlong in U.S. Customary units is thereafter defined based on the International 1959 foot, giving the length of the furlong as exact 201.168 meters in the United States as well.<ref>{{cite web |title=NGS and NIST to Retire U.S. Survey Foot after 2022 |url=https://www.ngs.noaa.gov/web/news/us-survey-foot.shtml |publisher=National Geodetic Survey |accessdate=4 March 2020 |date=31 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=U.S. Survey Foot: Revised Unit Conversion Factors |url=https://www.nist.gov/pml/us-surveyfoot/revised-unit-conversion-factors |publisher=NIST |accessdate=4 March 2020 |date=16 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[FFF system]]\n*[[Stadion (unit)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Customary units of measurement in the United States]]\n[[Category:Imperial units]]\n[[Category:Units of length]]\n[[Category:Surveying]]\n[[Category:Horse racing]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses}}\n{{short description|Unit of length equal to 660 feet or about 201 meters}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2012}}\n{{Infobox unit\n| standard = [[imperial units|imperial]]/[[US customary units|US]]&nbsp;units\n| quantity = [[length]]\n| units1   = imperial/US&nbsp;units\n| inunits1 = 220&nbsp;[[yard (unit)|yd]]\n| units2   = [[metric system|metric]] ([[SI]]) units\n| inunits2 = {{convert|220|yd|m|4|lk=on|disp=out}}\n}}\n{{Anthropic_Farm Units}}\n\nA '''furlong''' is a measure of [[distance]] in [[imperial units]] and [[U.S. customary units]] equal to one eighth of a [[mile]], equivalent to 660 [[foot (unit)|feet]], 220 [[yard]]s, 40 [[rod (unit)|rods]],  10 [[chain (unit)|chains]] or approximately 201 [[meter]]s.\n\nIn the [[United States]] some states use older definitions for surveying purposes, leading to variations in the length of the furlong of two parts per million, or about 0.4 millimetre ({{frac|64}} inch). This variation is too small to have practical consequences in most applications. \n \nUsing the international definition of the [[inch]] as exactly 25.4 [[millimetre]]s, one furlong is 201.168 metres. Five furlongs are about 1 [[kilometre]] ({{convert|5/8|mi|5|disp=out}} is the exact value, according to the international conversion).\n\n==History==\nThe name ''furlong'' derives from the [[Old English language|Old English]] words ''{{lang|ang|furh}}'' (furrow) and ''{{lang|ang|lang}}'' (long).<ref>{{Cite EB1911 |wstitle=Furlong |volume=11 |page=358}}</ref> Dating back at least to early [[Anglo-Saxon]] times, it originally referred to the length of the furrow in one [[acre]] of a ploughed [[open-field system|open field]] (a medieval communal field which was divided into strips). The furlong (meaning furrow length) was the distance a team of oxen could plough without resting. This was standardised to be exactly 40 rods or 10 chains. The system of long furrows arose because turning a team of oxen pulling a heavy plough was difficult. This offset the drainage advantages of short furrows and meant furrows were made as long as possible. An acre is an area that is one furlong long and one [[Chain (unit)|chain]] (66 feet or 22 yards) wide. For this reason, the furlong was once also called an '''acre's length''',<ref>{{cite book |title=[[The Winter's Tale]] |first=William |last=Shakespeare |authorlink=William Shakespeare |edition=unabridged|publisher=Courier Dover|year=2000 |isbn=9780486411187| page=5|quotation=footnote 17: ''heat an acre''; run a heat or course of an acre's length, \"acre\" being used as a lineal measure, equivalent to a furlong.}} {{Shakecite|WT|M|1|2}}</ref> though in modern usage an area of one acre can be of any shape. The term furlong, or '''shot''', was also used to describe a grouping of adjacent strips within an open field.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=1tgk_UNST2kC&lpg=PR28&dq=furlong%20shot%20strip%20field&pg=PR28#v=onepage |title=The English Village Community Examined in Its Relation to the Manorial and Tribal Systems and to the Common Or Open Field System of Husbandry: An Essay in Economic History|first=Frederic |last=Seebohm |publisher=Cambridge University Press |date=8 Dec 2011|page=4|isbn=9781108036344}}</ref>\n\nAmong the early Anglo-Saxons, the rod was the fundamental unit of land measurement. A furlong was 40 rods; an acre 4 by 40 rods, or 4 rods by 1 furlong, and thus 160 square rods. At the time, the Saxons used the North German foot, which was 10 percent longer than the foot of today. When England changed to the shorter foot in the late 13th century, rods and furlongs remained unchanged, since property boundaries were already defined in rods and furlongs. The only thing that changed was the number of feet and yards in a rod or a furlong, and the number of square feet and square yards in an acre. The definition of the rod went from 15 old feet to {{frac|16|1|2}} new feet, or from 5 old yards to {{frac|5|1|2}} new yards. The furlong went from 600 old feet to 660 new feet, or from 200 old yards to 220 new yards. The acre went from 36,000 old square feet to 43,560 new square feet, or from 4,000 old square yards to 4,840 new square yards.<ref>{{cite book|last=Zupko|first=Ronald Edward|authorlink=Ronald Edward Zupko|title=British weights & measures: a history from antiquity to the seventeenth century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pWUgAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=26 November 2011|year=1977|publisher=University of Wisconsin Press|isbn=978-0-299-07340-4|pages=10\u201311, 20\u201321}}</ref>\n\nThe furlong was historically viewed as being equivalent to the [[Ancient Roman units of measurement|Roman stade (''stadium'')]],<ref>Compare [[Josephus]], ''[[Antiquities of the Jews|Antiquities]]'' (15.11.3), who writes of the [[Temple Mount]] in Jerusalem that it was encompassed by a wall which measured one ''stadion'' ([[Greek language|Gr.]] \u03c3\u03c4\u03ac\u03b4\u03b9\u03bf\u03bd) to each angle, a word translated in English as \"furlong.\"</ref> which in turn derived from the [[Ancient Greek units of measurement|Greek system]]. For example, the [[King James Version|King James Bible]] uses the term \"furlong\" in place of the Greek ''stadion'', although more recent translations often use miles or kilometres in the main text and give the original numbers in footnotes.\n\nIn the Roman system, there were 625 feet to the ''stadium'', eight ''stadia'' to the mile, and three miles to the [[league (unit)|league]]. A league was considered to be the distance a man could walk in one hour, and the mile (from ''mille'', \"meaning thousand\") consisted of 1,000 ''passus'' (paces, five feet, or double-step).\n\nAfter the fall of the [[Western Roman Empire]], medieval Europe continued with the Roman system, which the people proceeded to diversify, leading to serious complications in trade, taxation, etc. Around the year 1300, by royal decree England standardized a long list of measures. Among the important units of distance and length at the time were the [[foot (unit)|foot]], [[yard]], [[rod (unit)|rod]] (or pole), furlong, and the [[mile]]. The rod was defined as {{frac|5|1|2}} yards or {{frac|16|1|2}} feet, and the mile was eight furlongs, so the definition of the furlong became 40 rods and that of the mile became 5,280 feet (eight furlongs/mile times 40 rods/furlong times {{frac|16|1|2}} feet/rod).\n\nA description from 1675 states, \"Dimensurator or Measuring Instrument whereof the mosts usual has been the Chain, and the common length for English Measures four Poles, as answering indifferently to the Englishs Mile and Acre, 10 such Chains in length making a Furlong, and 10 single square Chains an Acre, so that a square Mile contains 640 square Acres.\" \u2014John Ogilby, Britannia, 1675\n\nThe official use of the furlong was abolished in the United Kingdom under the [[Weights and Measures Acts of the United Kingdom|Weights and Measures Act]] 1985, an act that also abolished the official use of many other traditional units of measurement.\n\n==Use==\n[[File:Naypyitaw Tollbooth.jpg|right|thumb|Present-day use of furlongs on a highway sign near [[Yangon]]]]\n[[File:Milepost 358-6 on Yangon-Mandalay Expressway.JPG|right|thumb|Mileposts on the Yangon\u2013Mandalay Expressway use miles followed by furlongs]]\nIn [[Myanmar]], furlongs are currently used in conjunction with miles to indicate distances on highway signs. Mileposts on the [[Yangon\u2013Mandalay Expressway]] use miles and furlongs.\n\n[[File:036175 5 furlong.jpg|right|thumb|The five-furlong (1000 m) post on [[Epsom Derby|Epsom Downs]]]]\nIn the rest of the world, the furlong has very limited use, with the notable exception of [[horse racing]] in most English-speaking countries, including [[Canada]] and the [[United States]]. The distances for [[Horse racing#Australia|horse racing]] in Australia were converted to metric in 1972,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://museumvictoria.com.au/about/mv-news/2010/how-to-measure-a-racehorse/ |title=How to measure a racehorse |year=2010 |publisher=Museum Victoria |accessdate=21 June 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150621172623/http://museumvictoria.com.au/about/mv-news/2010/how-to-measure-a-racehorse/ |archive-date=21 June 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> but in the [[United Kingdom]],<ref>[http://www.sportinglife.com/racing/goodwood/course/ Example of the use of furlongs in horse racing] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629220021/http://www.sportinglife.com/racing/goodwood/course/ |date=29 June 2011 }}</ref> [[Ireland]], [[Canada]], and the [[United States]], races are still given in miles and furlongs. Also distances along the canals in English navigated by [[narrowboat]]s are commonly expressed in miles and furlongs.\n\nThe city of [[Roads and expressways in Chicago|Chicago's street numbering system]] allots a measure of 800 address units to each mile, in keeping with the city's system of eight blocks per mile. This means that every block in a typical Chicago neighborhood (in either North/South or East/West direction but rarely both) is approximately one furlong in length. [[Salt Lake City]]'s blocks are also each a square furlong in the downtown area. The blocks become less regular in shape farther from the center, but the numbering system (800 units to each mile) remains the same everywhere in [[Salt Lake County, Utah|Salt Lake County]]. Blocks in central [[Logan, Utah]], and in large sections of [[Phoenix, Arizona]], are similarly a square furlong in extent (eight to a mile, which explains the series of freeway exits: 19th Ave, 27th, 35th, 43rd, 51st, 59th \u2026). City blocks in the [[Hoddle Grid]] of [[Melbourne]] are also one furlong in length.\n\nMuch of [[Ontario]], Canada, was originally surveyed on a ten-furlong grid, with major roads being laid out along the grid lines. Now that distances are shown on road signs in kilometres, these major roads are almost exactly two kilometres apart. The exits on highways running through [[Toronto]], for example, are generally at intervals of two kilometres.<ref>[https://www.empm.ca/reports/Title%20Searches.pdf The Importance of Title Searches] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070709160457/http://www.empm.ca/reports/Title%20Searches.pdf |date=9 July 2007 }}</ref><ref>[http://wall-arm.ca/2011/04/land-titles-vs-land-registry Land Titles vs. Land Registry]</ref>\n\nThe furlong is also a base unit of the humorous [[FFF system]] of units.<ref name=\"SKB\">Stan Kelly-Bootle, \"[http://portal.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=1229919 As Big as a Barn?]\", ''ACM Queue'', March 2007, pp. 62\u201364.</ref>\n\n==Definition of length==\n<!-- This section is linked from the lead section -->\nThe exact length of the furlong varies slightly among English-speaking countries. In Canada<ref>\n[http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/W-6/ Weights and Measures Act, R.S.C., 1985], as amended; Schedule&nbsp;II, Canadian Units of Measurement.\n</ref> and the United Kingdom,<ref>\n[http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1985/72 Weights and Measures Act 1985], as amended; Schedule&nbsp;1,\nPart&nbsp;VI, Definitions of certain units which may not be used for trade except as supplementary indications.\n</ref> which define the furlong in terms of the international yard of exactly 0.9144 metres, a furlong is 201.168&nbsp;m.\nAustralia<ref>\n[http://www.comlaw.gov.au/Series/F1999B00110 National Measurement Regulations 1999], Statutory Rules 1999 No. 110 as amended, Schedule&nbsp;11, Conversion Factors.\n</ref> does not formally define the furlong, but it does define the chain and link in terms of the international yard.\n\nIn the United States, which defines the furlong, chain, rod, and [[link (unit)|link]] in terms of the [[U.S. survey foot]] of exactly {{fract|1200|3937}} metre,<ref>\nNIST Special Publication 811, Guide for the Use of the International System of Units (SI), [http://physics.nist.gov/Pubs/SP811/appenB.html Appendix&nbsp;B], B.6, U.S. survey foot and mile. National Institute for Standards and Technology, U.S. Department of Commerce, 2008.</ref> a furlong is approximately 201.1684 m long. The United States does not formally define a \"survey yard\". The difference of approximately two parts per million between the U.S. value and the \"international\" value is insignificant for most practical measurements.  \n\nIn October 2019, [[U.S. National Geodetic Survey]] and [[National Institute of Standards and Technology]] announced their joint intent to retire the U.S. survey foot, with effect from the end of 2022. The furlong in U.S. Customary units is thereafter defined based on the International 1959 foot, giving the length of the furlong as exact 201.168 meters in the United States as well.<ref>{{cite web |title=NGS and NIST to Retire U.S. Survey Foot after 2022 |url=https://www.ngs.noaa.gov/web/news/us-survey-foot.shtml |publisher=National Geodetic Survey |accessdate=4 March 2020 |date=31 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=U.S. Survey Foot: Revised Unit Conversion Factors |url=https://www.nist.gov/pml/us-surveyfoot/revised-unit-conversion-factors |publisher=NIST |accessdate=4 March 2020 |date=16 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[FFF system]]\n*[[Stadion (unit)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Customary units of measurement in the United States]]\n[[Category:Imperial units]]\n[[Category:Units of length]]\n[[Category:Surveying]]\n[[Category:Horse racing]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7f:8710:4b00:7502:3f43:4a51:218b", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Typo)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Furlong"}
{"title_page": "Murkha Nayanar", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox Hindu leader\n|name= Murkha Nayanar\n|image= Murkha Nayanar.JPG\n|caption =\n| religion = [[Hinduism]]\n|birth_place= [[Tiruverkadu]]\n|birth_name= \n|death_date= \n|death_place=  \n|philosophy= [[Shaivism]], [[Bhakti]]\n|honors= [[Nayanars|Nayanar]] Saint, \n|footnotes=\n}}\n\n'''Murkha Nayanar''', also known as '''Moorka Nayanar''', '''Murka Nayanar''', '''Moorkha Nayanar''', '''Murgga Nayanar''', '''Moorkka Nayanar''' and '''Murkhar''', is a [[Nayanars|Nayanar]] saint, venerated in the [[Hinduism|Hindu]] sect of [[Shaivism]]. He is generally counted as the thirty-second in the list of 63 Nayanars.<ref name=\"Dalal2011\">{{cite book|author=Roshen Dalal|title=Hinduism: An Alphabetical Guide|date=2011|publisher=Penguin Books India|isbn=978-0-14-341421-6|page=281}}</ref>\n\n==Life==\n[[File:Vedapureeswar temple, Thiruverkadu1.JPG|thumb|left|250px|[[Vedapureeswarar Temple, Thiruverkadu]] where there is a shrine of Murkha Nayanar]]\nThe life of Murkha Nayanar is described in the ''[[Periya Puranam]]'' by [[Sekkizhar]] (12th century), which is a hagiography of the 63 Nayanars.<ref name=\"Dalal2011\"/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.shaivam.org/english/sen_th12_moorkka.htm | title=The Puranam of Moorkka Nayanar | accessdate=12 December 2014 | author=T N Ramachandran}}</ref>\n\nMurkha was born in [[Tiruverkadu]] (Thiruverkadu), which was part of [[Tondai Nadu]], then part of the [[Pallava]] kingdom. Tiruverkadu is currently a western suburb of the Indian city of [[Chennai]]. He was a [[Vellalar]], a caste of agricultural land owners. He is described as great devotee of the god [[Shiva]], the patron god of Shaivism. Murkha Nayanar cultivated devotion for Shiva from his childhood. He used to serve Shiva, by serving Shaivas, the devotees of Shiva. He used to prepare rice with [[ghee]] and various sweet and savoury delicacies and feed the devotees. The saint spent all his wealth in feeding the devotees. He sold all his possessions, including his properties and his slaves.<ref name=\"Dehejia1988\"/><ref name=\"swami\"/>\n\nTo gain wealth and feed the devotees, Murkha turned to gambling and mastered \"the art\". Since people of Tiruverkadu did not want to gamble, he travelled to various towns, gambling and spending the money in serving Shiva and his devotees. He finally reached Tirukkudanthai (present-day [[Kumbakonam]]), home of numerous Shiva temples. To serve a feast to the devotees, he went to the gambling houses of the town. He strategically lost money in the initial rounds, forcing the opponents to gamble more money in the later rounds, winning great amount of money. He used to stab rivals, who cheated or used deception to win or refused to pay after losing. His actions earned him the name Murkha Nayanar, translated variously as \"wicked Nayanar\", \"fierce Nayanar\" and \"violent Nayanar\". The money was given to cooks, to prepare a feast for the devotees. He used to eat only after all the devotees had eaten. He lived his life, gambling and serving devotees, finally reaching [[Kailash]] - Shiva's abode, after his death.<ref name=\"Dehejia1988\">{{cite book|author=Vidya Dehejia|title=Slaves of the Lord: The Path of the Tamil Saints|year=1988|publisher=Munshiram Manoharlal|isbn=978-81-215-0044-9|pages=154\u20135, 177}}</ref><ref name=\"swami\">{{cite book | author = [[Swami Sivananda]] | title = Sixty-three Nayanar Saints | edition = 4 | publisher = The Divine Life Society | year = 1999 | location = Sivanandanagar }}</ref>\n\n==Remembrance==\n[[File:Sri Kokarneshvarar Temple in Tirukokarnam.JPG|thumb|The images of the Nayanars are found in many Shiva temples in Tamil Nadu.]]\n\nMurkha Nayanar is depicted with folded hands (see [[Anjali mudra]]). A holy day in his honour is observed in the [[Tamil calendar|Tamil month]] of [[Kartik (month)|Karthikai]] (November\u2013December).<ref name=\"Dehejia1988\"/> One of the most prominent Nayanars, [[Sundarar]] (7th century) refers to him as Murkkan (Murkha Nayanar) in a hymn to Nayanar saints. In another hymn to Shiva, he praises Shiva who accepts of the \"skillful gambler\" (''karra cutan''), a reference to Murkha Nayanar.<ref>{{cite book|title=Poems to \u015aiva: The Hymns of the Tamil Saints|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GPmq8fcOa9wC&pg=PA331|year=1991|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=978-81-208-0784-6|pages=333}}</ref>\n\nA shrine is dedicated to Murkha Nayanar in the outer corridor of the [[Vedapureeswarar Temple, Thiruverkadu|Vedapureeswarar Temple]], the Shiva temple in his home-town Tiruverkadu. A festival is celebrated in his honour in the month of Karthikai when the moon moves into the [[Nakshatra]] ([[Lunar mansion]]) of [[K\u1e5bttik\u0101|Krittika]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://temple.dinamalar.com/en/new_en.php?id=304 | title=Sri Vedapureeswarar temple | publisher=[[Dinamalar]] | accessdate=12 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nMurkha Nayanar is worshipped in the [[Tamil month]] of [[Kartik (month)|Karthikai]], when the moon enters the [[Mula (nakshatra)|Mula]] [[nakshatra]] (lunar mansion). He receives collective worship as part of the 63 Nayanars. Their icons and brief accounts of his deeds are found in many Shiva temples in [[Tamil Nadu]]. Their images are taken out in procession in festivals.<ref name=\"Dalal2011\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Nayanars}}\n\n[[Category:Nayanars]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox Hindu leader\n|name= Murkha Nayanar\n|image= Murkha Nayanar.JPG\n|caption =\n| religion = [[Hinduism]]\n|birth_place= [[Tiruverkadu]]\n|birth_name= \n|death_date= \n|death_place=  \n|philosophy= [[Shaivism]], [[Bhakti]]\n|honors= [[Nayanars|Nayanar]] saint, \n|footnotes=\n}}\n\n'''Murkha Nayanar''', also known as '''Moorka Nayanar''', '''Murka Nayanar''', '''Moorkha Nayanar''', '''Murgga Nayanar''', '''Moorkka Nayanar''' and '''Murkhar''', is a [[Nayanars|Nayanar]] saint, venerated in the [[Hinduism|Hindu]] sect of [[Shaivism]]. He is generally counted as the thirty-second in the list of 63 Nayanars.<ref name=\"Dalal2011\">{{cite book|author=Roshen Dalal|title=Hinduism: An Alphabetical Guide|date=2011|publisher=Penguin Books India|isbn=978-0-14-341421-6|page=281}}</ref>\n\n==Life==\n[[File:Vedapureeswar temple, Thiruverkadu1.JPG|thumb|left|250px|[[Vedapureeswarar Temple, Thiruverkadu]] where there is a shrine of Murkha Nayanar]]\nThe life of Murkha Nayanar is described in the ''[[Periya Puranam]]'' by [[Sekkizhar]] (12th century), which is a hagiography of the 63 Nayanars.<ref name=\"Dalal2011\"/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.shaivam.org/english/sen_th12_moorkka.htm | title=The Puranam of Moorkka Nayanar | accessdate=12 December 2014 | author=T N Ramachandran}}</ref>\n\nMurkha was born in [[Tiruverkadu]] (Thiruverkadu), which was part of [[Tondai Nadu]], then part of the [[Pallava]] kingdom. Tiruverkadu is currently a western suburb of the Indian city of [[Chennai]]. He was a [[Vellalar]], a caste of agricultural land owners. He is described as great devotee of the god [[Shiva]], the patron god of Shaivism. Murkha Nayanar cultivated devotion for Shiva from his childhood. He used to serve Shiva, by serving Shaivas, the devotees of Shiva. He used to prepare rice with [[ghee]] and various sweet and savoury delicacies and feed the devotees. The saint spent all his wealth in feeding the devotees. He sold all his possessions, including his properties and his slaves.<ref name=\"Dehejia1988\"/><ref name=\"swami\"/>\n\nTo gain wealth and feed the devotees, Murkha turned to gambling and mastered \"the art\". Since people of Tiruverkadu did not want to gamble, he travelled to various towns, gambling and spending the money in serving Shiva and his devotees. He finally reached Tirukkudanthai (present-day [[Kumbakonam]]), home of numerous Shiva temples. To serve a feast to the devotees, he went to the gambling houses of the town. He strategically lost money in the initial rounds, forcing the opponents to gamble more money in the later rounds, winning great amount of money. He used to stab rivals, who cheated or used deception to win or refused to pay after losing. His actions earned him the name Murkha Nayanar, translated variously as \"wicked Nayanar\", \"fierce Nayanar\" and \"violent Nayanar\". The money was given to cooks, to prepare a feast for the devotees. He used to eat only after all the devotees had eaten. He lived his life, gambling and serving devotees, finally reaching [[Kailash]] - Shiva's abode, after his death.<ref name=\"Dehejia1988\">{{cite book|author=Vidya Dehejia|title=Slaves of the Lord: The Path of the Tamil Saints|year=1988|publisher=Munshiram Manoharlal|isbn=978-81-215-0044-9|pages=154\u20135, 177}}</ref><ref name=\"swami\">{{cite book | author = [[Swami Sivananda]] | title = Sixty-three Nayanar Saints | edition = 4 | publisher = The Divine Life Society | year = 1999 | location = Sivanandanagar }}</ref>\n\n==Remembrance==\n[[File:Sri Kokarneshvarar Temple in Tirukokarnam.JPG|thumb|The images of the Nayanars are found in many Shiva temples in Tamil Nadu.]]\n\nMurkha Nayanar is depicted with folded hands (see [[Anjali mudra]]). A holy day in his honour is observed in the [[Tamil calendar|Tamil month]] of [[Kartik (month)|Karthikai]] (November\u2013December).<ref name=\"Dehejia1988\"/> One of the most prominent Nayanars, [[Sundarar]] (7th century) refers to him as Murkkan (Murkha Nayanar) in a hymn to Nayanar saints. In another hymn to Shiva, he praises Shiva who accepts of the \"skillful gambler\" (''karra cutan''), a reference to Murkha Nayanar.<ref>{{cite book|title=Poems to \u015aiva: The Hymns of the Tamil Saints|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GPmq8fcOa9wC&pg=PA331|year=1991|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=978-81-208-0784-6|pages=333}}</ref>\n\nA shrine is dedicated to Murkha Nayanar in the outer corridor of the [[Vedapureeswarar Temple, Thiruverkadu|Vedapureeswarar Temple]], the Shiva temple in his home-town Tiruverkadu. A festival is celebrated in his honour in the month of Karthikai when the moon moves into the [[Nakshatra]] ([[Lunar mansion]]) of [[K\u1e5bttik\u0101|Krittika]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://temple.dinamalar.com/en/new_en.php?id=304 | title=Sri Vedapureeswarar temple | publisher=[[Dinamalar]] | accessdate=12 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nMurkha Nayanar is worshipped in the [[Tamil month]] of [[Kartik (month)|Karthikai]], when the moon enters the [[Mula (nakshatra)|Mula]] [[nakshatra]] (lunar mansion). He receives collective worship as part of the 63 Nayanars. Their icons and brief accounts of his deeds are found in many Shiva temples in [[Tamil Nadu]]. Their images are taken out in procession in festivals.<ref name=\"Dalal2011\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Nayanars}}\n\n[[Category:Nayanars]]\n", "name_user": "BeckGoldberg", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Murkha_Nayanar"}
{"title_page": "Mark Lancaster", "text_new": "{{for|the British artist and set designer|Mark Lancaster (artist)}}\n{{short description|British Conservative politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[Colonel (United Kingdom)|Colonel]] [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = Mark Lancaster\n| honorific-suffix = {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100|TD|VR}}\n| image = Rt Hon Mark Lancaster TD MP.jpg\n| office = [[Minister of State for the Armed Forces]]\n| primeminister = [[Theresa May]]<br />[[Boris Johnson]]\n| term_start = 13 June 2017\n| term_end = 16 December 2019\n| predecessor = [[Mike Penning]]\n| successor = [[Anne-Marie Trevelyan]]\n| office1 = [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State]] [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|for Defence Veterans, Reserves and Personnel]]\n| primeminister1 = [[David Cameron]]<br />[[Theresa May]]\n| term_start1 = 12 May 2015\n| term_end1 = 13 June 2017\n| predecessor1 = [[Anna Soubry]]\n| successor1 = [[Tobias Ellwood]]\n| office2 = [[Junior Lord of the Treasury|Lord Commissioner of the Treasury]]\n| primeminister2 = [[David Cameron]]\n| term_start2 = 9 September 2012\n| term_end2 = 12 May 2015\n| predecessor2 = [[Jeremy Wright]]\n| successor2 = [[Charlie Elphicke]]\n| office4 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Milton Keynes North (UK Parliament constituency)|Milton Keynes North]]<br />[[North East Milton Keynes (UK Parliament constituency)|<small>North East Milton Keynes]]<br />(2005\u20132010)</small>\n| parliament4 = \n| majority4 = \n| term_start4 = 5 May 2005\n| term_end4 = 6 November 2019\n| predecessor4 = [[Brian White (British politician)|Brian White]]\n| successor4 = [[Ben Everitt]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1970|05|12|df=yes}}<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/mpdb/html/405.stm |title=Mark Lancaster |website=[[BBC News]] |date=13 February 2007 |accessdate=1 April 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090605205605/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/mpdb/html/405.stm |archivedate=5 June 2009 }}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Cambridge]], [[Cambridgeshire]], [[England]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = British\n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| residence = [[Olney, Buckinghamshire]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of Buckingham]]<br />[[University of Exeter]]\n| children = 2\n| spouse = {{marriage|Katherine Reader|1995|2007|end=divorced}}<br />{{marriage|[[Caroline Dinenage]]|2014}}\n| website = [http://www.lancaster4mk.com lancaster4mk.com]\n| footnotes = <!--Military service-->\n| allegiance = United Kingdom\n| branch = [[British Army Reserve]]\n| serviceyears = 1988\u2013present\n| rank = [[Colonel (United Kingdom)|Colonel]]\n| unit = Late [[Royal Engineers]]\n| commands = [[Tower Hamlets Engineers|217 (London) Field Squadron (EOD)]]\n| battles = [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]]\n| mawards = [[Efficiency Decoration]]<br />[[Volunteer Reserves Service Medal]]\n}}\n[[Colonel (United Kingdom)|Colonel]] '''John Mark Lancaster'''<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=62069 |date=3 October 2017 |page=18307 }}</ref>, {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100|sep=,|TD|VR}} (born 12 May 1970) is a British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician, who served as [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Milton Keynes North (UK Parliament constituency)|Milton Keynes North]] from the seat's creation at the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]] until his retirement in [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019]], having been [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for the [[North East Milton Keynes (UK Parliament constituency)|North East Milton Keynes]] constituency between 2005 and 2010. He served as a Minister in several appointments after the formation of the Coalition Government in 2010, first as Lord Commissioner of Her Majesty's Treasury, before in May 2015 moving to the Ministry of Defence as the Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for Veterans, Reserves and Personnel, then on the 13 June 2017, he was appointed [[Minister of State for the Armed Forces]] in the [[Second May ministry]] and was reappointed by [[Boris Johnson]] at the start of his Premiership in July 2019, he served in this role until his retirement from Government on the 16th Dec 2019.\n\n==Ministerial career==\n\nAfter his re-election in 2010, he was initially appointed as the [[Parliamentary Private Secretary|PPS]] to the [[Secretary of State for International Development]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dfid.gov.uk/Documents/aboutdfid/organogram.pdf |title=Ministers and Senior Management Organisation Chart |website=Department for International Development |date=November 2017 |accessdate=7 December 2017}}</ref> Lancaster was appointed Lord Commissioner of Her Majesty's Treasury in September 2012. He was appointed Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Defence Personnel, and Veterans at the Ministry of Defence following the formation of the [[second Cameron ministry]] on 12 May 2015. He was reappointed by Theresa May on her becoming prime minister in June 2016 and had Reserves added to his portfolio, changing job title to Minister for Defence Veterans, Reserves and Personnel. He was promoted to Minister of State for the Armed Forces after the 2017 general election. \nHe was appointed to the Privy Council in November 2017. \nIn November 2019 he announced his retirement from Parliament.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-50275204|title=Mark Lancaster to stand down as Milton Keynes North MP|publisher=BBC News|date=2 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nLancaster was born on 12 May 1970 in Cambridge. He was privately educated at [[Kimbolton School]] in Huntingdonshire where his father [[Ronald Lancaster (chemist)|Ronald Lancaster]] was chaplain.<ref name=DMail1159899>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1159899/The-modern-face-Tory-Party-Front-bencher-splits-mother-baby--shell-voting-Labour.html |title=Lover splits from high-flying Tory MP and says she'll now vote Labour |first=Andy |last=Dolan |newspaper=[[Daily Mail]] |date=7 March 2009 |accessdate=5 March 2014 |location=London}}</ref> He graduated as a [[Bachelor of Science|BSc]] in Business Studies from the [[University of Buckingham]] and [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]] from the [[University of Exeter]] Business School.  He was awarded an Honorary [[PhD]] from Buckingham in 2008.<ref name=\"con\">{{cite web |url=http://www.conservatives.com/People/Members_of_Parliament/Lancaster_Mark.aspx |title=Biography of Mark Lancaster |website=Conservative Party |accessdate=18 July 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090414153532/http://www.conservatives.com/People/Members_of_Parliament/Lancaster_Mark.aspx |archive-date=14 April 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nHe was a [[company director]] for the family  firm [[Kimbolton Fireworks]] before he was elected to Parliament.<ref name=DMail1159899/>\n\n==Military career==\nBetween 1988 and 1990 Lancaster served in the [[British Army]] on an extended [[gap year]] Commission in Hong Kong with the [[Queen's Gurkha Engineers]] before going to university.  He then transferred his Commission to the [[Territorial Army (United Kingdom)|Army Reserve]] where he continues to serve as a in the General Staff Corps ( Late [[Royal Engineers]] ), having previously commanded an [[Explosive Ordnance Disposal]] unit.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.army.mod.uk/royalengineers/units/28649.aspx?p=28664 |title=Bomb Disposal and Search Specialists |website=British Army |accessdate=7 December 2017}}</ref> He has been on active service three times in [[Kosovo]] (1999\u20132000), [[Bosnia]] (2001\u20132002) and [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|Afghanistan]] (2006).<ref name=DMail1159899/> He is currently Deputy Commander of [[77th Brigade (United Kingdom)|77th Brigade]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forces.net/news/new-line-ministry-defence|title=The New Line Up At The Ministry Of Defence|date=10 January 2018|publisher=Ministry of Defence|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe received a number of military honours and decorations between 2000 and 2016, including the [[Territorial Decoration]] (TD) in 2002 and the [[Volunteer Reserves Service Medal]] (VRSM) in 2011. He was awarded the Bar for a further five years service in 2016.\n\nHe was appointed as the Deputy Colonel Commandant Brigade of Gurkhas on 1 September 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk|date=5 November 2019|page =19879|accessdate=23 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe was appointed Chair of the Reserve Forces 2030 review in January 2020.{{citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\n==Non-Ministerial political career==\nLancaster stood unsuccessfully as the Conservative candidate for the Huntingdon West ward on [[Huntingdonshire]] District Council in 1994, before being elected in the Ellington ward in 1995. He served as the chairman of the Leisure Committee (1996\u20131999). He lost his council seat in the local elections in 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.electionscentre.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/Huntingdonshire-1973-2011.pdf|title=Huntingdonshire Council Election Results 1973\u20132011|publisher= Plymouth University|accessdate=8 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nLancaster stood unsuccessfully as the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] candidate for [[Nuneaton (UK Parliament constituency)|Nuneaton]] at the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 general election]]. He was defeated by the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] candidate [[Bill Olner]].\n\nLancaster was elected as [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] gaining [[North East Milton Keynes (UK Parliament constituency)|North East Milton Keynes]] for the Conservatives in the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]], and succeeding [[Brian White (British politician)|Brian White]] of the Labour Party.\n\nDuring his time as a backbench MP, He served on the Office of Deputy Prime Minister Select Committee, (2005), Defence Select Committee (2006),<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/person/6047/mark-lancaster |title=Mark Lancaster: Electoral history and profile |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian News and Media]] |accessdate=30 July 2009 |location=London}}</ref> Housing, Communities and Local Government Committee (2008\u201309) and the International Development Select Committee (2009\u201310).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.uk/parliamentary_committees/international_development/international_development_members.cfm |title=International Development Committee: Members |website=[[Parliament of the United Kingdom]] |accessdate=30 July 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090925141223/http://www.parliament.uk/parliamentary_committees/international_development/international_development_members.cfm |archivedate=25 September 2009  }}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, he introduced a [[Ten Minute Rule]] Bill in the House that would allow local councils to ban glasses and bottles in late night clubs and bars and replace them with plastic in support of his constituent Blake Golding. Lancaster also submitted an [[early day motion]] in 2006 calling for the government to ban sales of alcohol in glass containers in bars after 11&nbsp;pm.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.peterboroughtoday.co.uk/news/latest-news/a-year-in-the-life-of-milton-keynes-1-857849 |title=A year in the life of Milton Keynes |newspaper=[[Peterborough Evening Telegraph]] |date=27 December 2006 |accessdate=7 April 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmhansrd/vo060619/debtext/60619-0001.htm |title=House of Commons 19 Jun 2006 : Column 1047  |website=[[Parliament of the United Kingdom]] |accessdate=7 April 2015 }}</ref>\n\nHe was the (unpaid) parliamentary advisor to the [[Royal Society of Chemistry]] until his promotion to minister in 2012.<ref name=\"work\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/mark_lancaster/north_east_milton_keynes |title=Mark Lancaster MP, Milton Keynes North |website=[[TheyWorkForYou]] |accessdate=15 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, he was a member of the special select committee set up to scrutinise the Bill that became the [[Armed Forces Act 2011]].<ref>{{cite web |url =  https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201011/cmselect/cmarmed/779/77901.htm |accessdate =  20 September 2013\n|title =  Select Committee on the Armed Forces Bill |website =  Parliament of the United Kingdom}}</ref> He was also a member of the [[Public Bill Committee]] for the [[Defence Reform Act 2014]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://services.parliament.uk/bills/2013-14/defencereform/committees/houseofcommonspublicbillcommitteeonthedefencereformbill201314.html |title=House of Commons Public Bill Committee on the Defence Reform Bill 2013\u201314 |website=Parliament of the United Kingdom |date= |accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2017, he was made a member of the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Council]].<ref name=\"www.gov.uk\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/queen-approves-new-members-of-the-privy-council-14-november-2017 |title=Queen approves new members of the Privy Council |date=14 November 2017 |website=GOV.UK |accessdate=7 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Political views===\nLancaster has stated his disagreement with the UK Government's policy on the [[Iraq War|2003 invasion of Iraq]]. In an interview with the [[BBC]], he stated \"It may well be much harder to get the British public to back other overseas adventures by the military because of what's happened in Iraq\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6462665.stm |title=Iraq: has it changed UK politics? |website=[[BBC News]] |first=Mark |last=Easton |authorlink=Mark Easton |date=20 March 2007 |accessdate=15 September 2010}}</ref> According to the [[Public Whip]], he voted strongly against the introduction of ID cards and in favour of a smoking ban and an investigation into the Iraq war. In votes involving transparency of parliament (including MPs expenses),<ref name=\"whip\">{{cite web |url=http://www.publicwhip.org.uk/mp.php?mpid=1715&dmp=996/ |title=Mark Lancaster compared to 'Transparency of Parliament' |website=[[Public Whip]]|accessdate=15 September 2010}}</ref> [[gay rights]], and [[climate change]] his voting record is not easily categorized by obvious stereotypes, although in early 2013, Lancaster voted against legislation allowing gay couples to marry at second reading but supported minor 'tidying up' legislation supporting the principle once the main Bill had passed through the House of Commons.<ref name=\"work\" /> He later tweeted in July 2016 that he had been wrong to have opposed second reading.\n\nIn 2011 Lancaster introduced his own [[Private Members Bill]], which enabled special Olympic 1&nbsp;kg gold and silver coins to be struck by the [[Royal Mint]] as part of the 2012 Olympic legacy. These were launched by the Royal Mint. In 2013 Lancaster was successful in his four-year campaign to get [[Khat]] classified as a category C drug following calls from his constituents.\n\n==Personal life==\nLancaster lives in Gosport with his wife, Conservative MP for Gosport [[Caroline Dinenage]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theipsa.org.uk/mp-costs/your-mp/jack-brereton/http://www.theipsa.org.uk/mp-costs/your-mp/mark-lancaster/|title=IPSA record|publisher=IPSA|date= |accessdate=8 September 2018}}</ref> He previously married Katherine Reader 1995 before separating in 2006 and divorcing in 2009. He briefly partnered Amanda Evans with whom he has a daughter. In February 2014, he married Caroline Dinenage, who had also been previously married.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.miltonkeynes.co.uk/news/city-mp-splits-from-mother-of-his-baby-1-868457|title=GCity MP splits from mother of his baby|website=MK Citizen|date=5 March 2009 |accessdate=8 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.portsmouth.co.uk/news/gosport-mp-caroline-dinenage-weds-fellow-politician-at-house-of-commons-chapel-1-5881270 |title=Gosport MP Caroline Dinenage weds fellow politician at House of Commons chapel |website=Portsmouth News |date=17 February 2014 |accessdate=5 March 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912191955/http://www.portsmouth.co.uk/news/gosport-mp-caroline-dinenage-weds-fellow-politician-at-house-of-commons-chapel-1-5881270 |archive-date=12 September 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Lancaster is a supporter of [[MK Dons]], and enjoys playing [[cricket]], which includes the House of Commons team.<ref name=DMail1159899/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.mk-news.co.uk/mknews-news/displayarticle.asp?id=106763 |title=The home of cricket resounds to the sound of leather on Campbell Park willow |newspaper=[[MK News]] |publisher=Local Sunday Newspapers |date=4 July 2007 |accessdate=8 July 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=July 2019}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- bgcolor=\"silver\" align=\"center\"\n|Ribbon || Description || Notes\n|-\n|[[File:NATO Medal w S\u0142u\u017cbie Pokoju i Wolno\u015bci BAR.svg|100px]] || [[NATO Medal]] for Kosovo ||\n* 2000\n|-\n|[[File:NATO Medal Yugoslavia ribbon bar.svg|100px]] || [[NATO Medal|NATO Former Republic of Yugoslavia Medal]] || \n* 2002\nWith clasp ' ''Former Yugoslavia'' '\n|-\n|[[File:OSM for Afghanistan w bar.svg|100px]] || [[Operational Service Medal for Afghanistan|OSM for Afghanistan]] ||\n* 2006\n* With \"AFGHANISTAN\" Clasp\n|-\n|[[File:Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|100px]] || [[Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal]] || \n* 2002\n* UK Version of this Medal\n|-\n|[[File:QEII Diamond Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|100px]] || [[Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Medal]] || \n* 2012\n* UK Version of this Medal\n|-\n|[[File:Efficiency Decoration (Territorial & Volunteer Reserve).png|100px]] || [[Efficiency Decoration]] (TD) ||\n* 2002\n* 12 Years Commissioned Service in the [[Army Reserve (United Kingdom)|Territorial Army]]\n|-\n|[[File:Volunteer Reserves Service Medal.png|100px]] || [[Volunteer Reserves Service Medal]] || \n* 2011\n* 2016 bar for 5 years further service\n* 10 Years Service in the [[Army Reserve (United Kingdom)|Army Reserves]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.lancaster4mk.com Personal website of Mark Lancaster MP]\n* {{UK MP links |parliament = mark-lancaster/1544 |hansardcurr = 4803 |publicwhip = Mark_Lancaster |theywork = mark_lancaster}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090414153532/http://www.conservatives.com/People/Members_of_Parliament/Lancaster_Mark.aspx National Conservative Party profile on Mark Lancaster]\n* [http://www.mkconservatives.com/ Milton Keynes Conservative Association website]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Brian White (British politician)|Brian White]]}}\n{{s-ttl\n  |title  = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[North East Milton Keynes (UK Parliament constituency)|North East Milton Keynes]]\n  |years  = [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]]\u2013[[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]\n}}\n{{s-non|reason=Constituency replaced by [[Milton Keynes North (UK Parliament constituency)|Milton Keynes North]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-non|reason=Constituency created from [[North East Milton Keynes (UK Parliament constituency)|North East Milton Keynes]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Milton Keynes North (UK Parliament constituency)|Milton Keynes North]]|years=[[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]\u2013[[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ben Everitt]]}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|befor